paragraphs.title: 3 - Create an RDD for the web logs
paragraphs.text:
%md
In Spark, create an RDD from the uploaded web logs data files in `/user/zeppelin/weblogs/`.

msg.data:
In Spark, create an RDD from the uploaded web logs data files in the
/devsh_loudacre/weblogs/ directory in HDFS.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
logsRDD = sc.textFile("/user/zeppelin/weblogs/")

paragraphs.title: 4 - Create an RDD using the filter operation
paragraphs.text:
%md
Create an RDD containing only lines that are requests for JPG files. Use the `filter` operation with a transformation function that takes a string RDD element and returns a boolean value.

msg.data:
Create an RDD containing only lines that are requests for JPG files. Use the filter
operation with a transformation function that takes a string RDD element and
returns a boolean value.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
jpglogsRDD = logsRDD.filter(lambda line: ".jpg" in line)

paragraphs.text:
%md
Use `take` to return the first five lines of the data in `jpglogsRDD`. The return value is a list of strings (in Python) or array of strings (in Scala).

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
jpgLines = jpglogsRDD.take(5)

paragraphs.title: 7 - Use the map transformation to define a new RDD
paragraphs.text:
%md
Use the `map` transformation to define a new RDD. Start with a simple map function that returns the length of each line in the log file. This results in an RDD of integers.

msg.data:
Use the map transformation to define a new RDD. Start with a simple map function
that returns the length of each line in the log file. This results in an RDD of integers.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
lineLengthsRDD = logsRDD.map(lambda line: len(line))

paragraphs.text:

paragraphs.title: 9 - Split the strings in the RDD using map
paragraphs.text:
%md
Calculating line lengths is not very useful. Instead, try mapping each string in `logsRDD` by splitting the strings based on spaces. The result will be an RDD in which each element is a list of strings.

msg.data:
Calculating line lengths is not very useful. Instead, try mapping each string in
logsRDD by splitting the strings based on spaces. The result will be an RDD in
which each element is a list of strings (in Python) or an array of strings (in Scala).
Each string represents a “field” in the web log line.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
lineFieldsRDD = logsRDD.map(lambda line: line.split(' '))

paragraphs.title: 10 - Return the first five elements of the new RDD
paragraphs.text:
%md
Return the first five elements of `lineFieldsRDD`. The result will be a list of lists of strings.

msg.data:
Return the first five elements of lineFieldsRDD. The result will be a list of lists of
strings (in Python) or an array of arrays of strings (in Scala).

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
lineFields = lineFieldsRDD.take(5)

paragraphs.title: 11 - Display the contents returned from take
paragraphs.text:
%md
Display the contents of the return from `take`. Unlike in examples above, which returned collections of simple values (strings and ints), this time you have a set of compound values (lists containing strings). Therefore, to display them properly, you will need to loop through the arrays/lists in `lineFields`, and then loop through each string in the array/list. To make it easier to read the output, print `-------` to separate each set of field values.

msg.data:
Display the contents of the return from take. Unlike in examples above, which
returned collections of simple values (strings and ints), this time you have a set of
compound values (arrays or lists containing strings). Therefore, to display them
properly, you will need to loop through the arrays/lists in lineFields, and then
loop through each string in the array/list. To make it easier to read the output, print
------- to separate each set of field values.

If you choose to copy and paste the Pyspark code below into the shell, it may not
automatically indent properly; be sure the indentation is correct before executing
the command.

for fields in lineFields:
    print "-------"
    for field in fields: print field

paragraphs.title: 12 - Use map to create a new RDD containing just IP addresses
paragraphs.text:
%md
Now that you know how `map` works, create a new RDD containing just the IP
addresses from each line in the log file. (The IP address is the first space-delimited
field in each line.)

%pyspark
ipsRDD = logsRDD.map(lambda line: line.split(' ')[0])
for ip in ipsRDD.take(5): print ip

paragraphs.title: 13 - Save the list of IP addresses to a text file
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
ipsRDD.saveAsTextFile("/user/zeppelin/iplist")

26 - Create an RDD from the source dataset
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
files="/user/zeppelin/activations"
activationFiles = sc.wholeTextFiles(files)

paragraphs.title: 27 - Create a new RDD from the activation records extracted from the XML strings
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
activationRecords = activationFiles.flatMap(lambda pair: getActivations(pair[1]))

paragraphs.title: 28 - Extract the account number and model from each activation record
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
models = activationRecords.map(lambda record: getAccount(record) + ":" + getModel(record))

paragraphs.title: 29 - Save the formatted strings to a text file
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
models.saveAsTextFile("/user/zeppelin/account-models")
